{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-lesson-template-js","path":"/deploying/deploy-deno-image","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h2 id=\"prerequisites\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#prerequisites\" aria-label=\"prerequisites permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Prerequisites</h2>\n<p>To complete this section, you'll need the following things...</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.microsoft.com/cli/azure/install-azure-cli?WT.mc_id=devcloud-0000-buhollan\">Azure CLI</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/free/\">Free Azure Account</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now that we've pushed the image to Docker hub, we can pull it in from a cloud hosting provider. Nearly all providers support containers. For the purposes of this section, we'll be using Azure.</p>\n<h2 id=\"creating-the-site\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#creating-the-site\" aria-label=\"creating the site permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Creating the site</h2>\n<p>The Azure Service that we need to host a website in a container is called \"App Service\". App Service allows you to host a container in Azure with your website inside.</p>\n<p>Using the Azure CLI, make sure you are logged in...</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">az login</code></pre></div>\n<p>Next, create a Resource Group. Resource Groups are just how Azure resources are organized. You can think of them like projects. A project might have a database, a website, some analytics - all of those are different Azure services, but we would want them all in the same resource group to help us stay organized.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">az group create -l westus -n <span class=\"token string\">\"deno-exercise-group\"</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Now we need to specify what sort of computing power we want for the site we're going to create. That's done with something called \"service plans\". A service plan says what kind of operating system you want - Windows or Linux - and how much compute you need. This is where you are spending money in so much as you get what you pay for. For this demonstration, we'll use the F1 - which is the free tier. Finally, we're specifying that we want Linux hosting as Windows is the default.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">az appservice plan create -g deno-exercise-group -n deno-service-plan --sku F1 --is-linux</code></pre></div>\n<p>Last, we create the site and tell it to pull our image from Docker hub.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">az webapp create -n deno-exercise -g deno-exercise-group -p deno-service-plan -i burkeholland/denoexercises</code></pre></div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Web app names in Azure have to be unique, so if the command fails, try a different name than \"deno-exercise\".</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Let's just review what all those flags were, cause there are a few of them...</p>\n<ul>\n<li>-n = name of the web app</li>\n<li>-g = name of the Resource Group</li>\n<li>-p = name of the Service Plan</li>\n<li>-i = name of the image to pull and run</li>\n</ul>\n<p>It takes just a minute for the site to start the container for the first time. You can find the URL for your new site by looking at the output from the last command (there is a lot of it - I know) and finding the \"defaultHostName\" property...</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/deno-first-look/static/49d9cbdfd94881b665b26bd907005e61/7355e/default-hostname.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 41.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"default hostname\"\n        title=\"default hostname\"\n        src=\"/deno-first-look/static/49d9cbdfd94881b665b26bd907005e61/a24e6/default-hostname.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/deno-first-look/static/49d9cbdfd94881b665b26bd907005e61/a6b4f/default-hostname.jpg 200w,\n/deno-first-look/static/49d9cbdfd94881b665b26bd907005e61/a6407/default-hostname.jpg 400w,\n/deno-first-look/static/49d9cbdfd94881b665b26bd907005e61/a24e6/default-hostname.jpg 800w,\n/deno-first-look/static/49d9cbdfd94881b665b26bd907005e61/7355e/default-hostname.jpg 969w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Copy that URL and paste it into a browser tab and...</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/deno-first-look/static/09bc38def8ce44351a1d9d44e98fe12c/01766/deno-deployed.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 29.500000000000004%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"deno deployed\"\n        title=\"deno deployed\"\n        src=\"/deno-first-look/static/09bc38def8ce44351a1d9d44e98fe12c/a24e6/deno-deployed.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/deno-first-look/static/09bc38def8ce44351a1d9d44e98fe12c/a6b4f/deno-deployed.jpg 200w,\n/deno-first-look/static/09bc38def8ce44351a1d9d44e98fe12c/a6407/deno-deployed.jpg 400w,\n/deno-first-look/static/09bc38def8ce44351a1d9d44e98fe12c/a24e6/deno-deployed.jpg 800w,\n/deno-first-look/static/09bc38def8ce44351a1d9d44e98fe12c/01766/deno-deployed.jpg 978w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Rock and roll! We successfully built a full-on web app with Deno and deployed it to a proper cloud.</p>","frontmatter":{"path":"/deploying/deploy-deno-image","title":"Deploying the Deno image","order":"8C","section":"8 - Deploying","description":"Burke looks at how to deploy an application built with Deno"}},"allMarkdownRemark":{"edges":[{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"4D","path":"/dependencies/best-practices","titl